# Overview

This project examines spatial accessibility to childcare in Mecklenburg County,
North Carolina using a Two-Step Floating Catchment Area (2SFCA) framework.
Accessibility scores were modeled across multiple dimensions of effective access,
including licensed capacity, provider quality, subsidy acceptance, and
transportation mode.

The analysis integrates:
- ACS demographic data
- OpenStreetMap road networks
- CATS GTFS transit feeds
- NC childcare facility licensing data
- Multimodal travel time modeling using `r5r`

# Key Findings

- Accessibility declines substantially when restricting supply to subsidized
  high-quality providers.
- Transit-based access to childcare is limited across much of Mecklenburg
  County.
- PCA results suggest childcare accessibility operates partly independently
  from broader socioeconomic vulnerability patterns.

